{# ============================================================
   LIFE STORY
============================================================ #}
<section class="suresh-section suresh-story" id="story">
  <div class="suresh-container">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Our Wonderful Friend</h2>

    <p class="story-text">
      Suresh Jagmohan Shah was born on February 9, 1940 to the late Jagmohan and Madhu Shah.
      He immigrated to the US in 1967 to complete his education and begin his career, earning his master's
      degree in mechanical engineering from West Virginia University. On April 11, 1969 he married Pratibha Shah
      and they built a life together in Columbus and Newark, Ohio. He worked as an engineer for several companies
      including RCA, Owens-Corning, and Rockwell, and retired in 2005.
    </p>

    <p class="story-text">
      Suresh had a way of bringing joy to every room and of making every person feel special. When he saw you
      he'd say <em>"How's my wonderful friend?"</em> If you were lucky, he'd put his hand on your shoulder and
      look you right in the eye. You left every encounter with him feeling better than when you arrived.
      That was his gift.
    </p>

    <p class="story-text">
      No matter who you were, Suresh would find a way to connect with you. He loved to read and learn and
      knew a little something about almost everything. He was curious to know what fascinated you, what you
      were passionate about — and then he'd meet you there (even if you were a Michigan fan).
    </p>

    <p class="story-text">
      Once he knew what you were into, he'd send you texts and articles to show you he was thinking about you.
      When he learned that his grandson Jaden loved Tottenham Hotspur, he started watching soccer so they'd
      have something to share. He had never watched soccer before. It wasn't really about soccer — it was
      about loving his grandson. He did this with almost everyone he met.
    </p>

    <p class="story-text">
      Somewhere along the way, he became one of Ohio State's biggest fans. On game days, no one yelled louder.
      He was always the first to shout <em>"O-H!"</em> and wait for the <em>"I-O!"</em>
      He got a kick out of doing it in random places too.
    </p>

    <p class="story-text">
      During the last year of his life, he began writing emails to the Men's and Women's Ohio State basketball
      coaches, always signing them <em>"Buckeye Uncle."</em> He'd offer words of encouragement and sometimes
      a touch of advice about how to get the most out of their teams. Women's coach Kevin McGuff wrote him back,
      and they became unlikely pen pals.
    </p>

    <p class="story-text">
      He never tried to tell you how to live. He simply lived in a way that made you want to live more peacefully
      and more happily. If you watched carefully, you'd discover the magic of accepting life as it comes without
      resistance. To the very end, if you asked him how he was doing he'd say <em>"fantastic."</em>
      His hope, joy, and positivity never wavered. It's who he was.
    </p>

    <p class="story-text">
      He had one desire in life — to make people smile. By that measure, his life was a resounding success.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

